<item>
            <title>[KAFKA-5936] KafkaProducer should not wrap InterruptedException in close() with KafkaException</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-5936</link>
                <project id="12311720" key="KAFKA">Kafka</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;KafkaProducer.close()&lt;/tt&gt; catches an &lt;tt&gt;InterruptedException&lt;/tt&gt; when joining the sender thread and rethrows it later as a &lt;tt&gt;KafkaException&lt;/tt&gt;. This prevent the interrupt signal to bubble out of the producer and thus, the caller might miss the interrupt.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We should rather throw our own &lt;tt&gt;org.apache.kafka.common.errors.InterruptException&lt;/tt&gt; similar to &lt;tt&gt;KafkaConsumer&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment></environment>
        <key id="13103429">KAFKA-5936</key>
